Conditional statements

Conditional statements let a program make decisions based on whether conditions are true or false.
They control the flow of execution.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš™ï¸ 1. Basic if Statement

Used to execute a block only if the condition is true.

// Java
int age = 20;
if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible to vote");
}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš™ï¸ 2. ifâ€“else Statement

Executes one block if true, another if false.

// Java
int num = 5;
if (num % 2 == 0)
    System.out.println("Even");
else
    System.out.println("Odd");
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    
    
âš™ï¸ 3. Nested if

if inside another if (use carefully; can reduce readability).

// Java
int num = 10;
if (num > 0) {
    if (num % 2 == 0)
        System.out.println("Positive Even");
}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš™ï¸ 4. ifâ€“else ifâ€“else Ladder

Used when checking multiple conditions sequentially.

// Java
int marks = 85;
if (marks >= 90)
    System.out.println("A Grade");
else if (marks >= 75)
    System.out.println("B Grade");
else
    System.out.println("C Grade");
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    
âš™ï¸ 5. switch / match Statement

Used for multi-branch decision-making.

// Java
int day = 3;
switch (day) {
    case 1: System.out.println("Monday"); break;
    case 2: System.out.println("Tuesday"); break;
    case 3: System.out.println("Wednesday"); break;
    default: System.out.println("Invalid Day");
}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš™ï¸ 6. Ternary Operator (Shortcut)

Used for concise ifâ€“else operations.

// Java
int num = 10;
String result = (num % 2 == 0) ? "Even" : "Odd";
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš™ï¸ 7. Edge Cases

Floating point comparisons (avoid == for floats due to precision)
Null checks in Java before comparison
Indentation-sensitive syntax in Python
Fall-through behavior in C++/Java switch (use break)


| Feature              | Java                                   | C++                                   | Python                                  |
|----------------------|----------------------------------------|---------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|
| Basic Structure      | if, else if, else, switch              | if, else if, else, switch             | if, elif, else, match                    |
| Boolean Condition    | Must return boolean                    | Can use any integral or bool          | Truthy or falsy expressions              |
| Block Scope          | Uses braces `{}`                       | Uses braces `{}`                      | Uses indentation                         |
| Switch Expression    | Added from Java 14 (arrow syntax)      | Classic switch                        | Introduced `match-case` from Python 3.10 |
| Ternary Operator     | Yes (`? :`)                            | Yes (`? :`)                           | Yes (`x if cond else y`)                 |
| Default Execution    | `default:` block                       | `default:` block                      | `case _:` block                          |
| Fall-through Allowed | Yes, without `break`                   | Yes, without `break`                  | No (each case isolated)                  |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


ðŸ§  Deep Dive Insights
Java requires strictly boolean conditions (if (x) wonâ€™t compile if x isnâ€™t boolean).
C++ allows non-boolean conditions (if (5) is valid and true).
Python treats 0, None, empty strings/lists as False.
Switch vs ifâ€“else: Use switch for discrete values, if for ranges or complex conditions.
Python match-case: pattern matching supports destructuring, not just value equality.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš™ï¸ 1. Java 14+ Enhanced switch Expressions

Traditional switch was a statement â€” it didnâ€™t return a value.
The enhanced version is an expression, meaning it can yield a value directly.

âœ… Syntax
String day = "MON";
String type = switch (day) {
    case "MON", "TUE", "WED", "THU", "FRI" -> "Weekday";
    case "SAT", "SUN" -> "Weekend";
    default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid day: " + day);
};
System.out.println(type);


ðŸ” Key Features
Arrow (->) replaces : and break.
Multiple labels per case (like "MON", "TUE").
Can return a value (unlike old switch).
Supports yield keyword for block logic.

int num = 3;
String result = switch (num) {
    case 1 -> "One";
    case 2 -> "Two";
    case 3 -> {
        String s = "Three";
        yield s + " (yielded)";
    }
    default -> "Unknown";
};
System.out.println(result);


ðŸ§  Why it matters: This design eliminates fall-through bugs and allows functional-style 
decision making. Java finally caught up with expressive syntax while staying type-safe.

| Feature / Language       | Java (>=14)                         | C++17+                                  | Python (>=3.10)                             |
|--------------------------|-------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|
| Syntax Type              | Expression-based switch             | Still statement-based                   | Structural pattern matching                 |
| Fall-through             | Disallowed by default               | Allowed unless `break` used             | Not possible                                |
| Multiple labels per case | Supported (case A, B ->)            | Supported via chained if                | Supported (A | B)                           |
| Returns value            | Yes (expression form)               | No (but can simulate)                   | Yes (via variable assignment)               |
| Works with strings       | Yes                                 | No (only integral types)                | Yes                                         |
| Destructuring patterns   | No                                  | No                                      | Yes                                         |
| Guards / Conditions      | No (use if before)                  | Yes (`if` chain)                        | Yes (`if` after case)                       |
| Purpose                  | Safe, concise branching             | Compile-time control & performance      | Pattern-based logic matching                |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


